time required: 20 minutes
---

Boil a #kettle{} full.

Pour the boiled water into a large #saucepan{} with @salt{1/4%tsp} on high heat.
Add the @Basmati Rice{150%g} and cook for ~{10-12%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain in a #sieve{} and pop back in the pan. Cover with a #lid{}
and leave to the side until ready to serve.

While the rice cooks, peel and grate the @garlic{1%clove} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Heat a drizzle of @oil{a drizzle} in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Add the @korma curry paste{50%g}, @garam masala{1%tsp} and garlic. Cook,
stirring, for ~{1%minute}.

Stir the @diced chicken breast{260%g}, @finely chopped tomatoes{1/2%can},
@water{100%ml} and @sugar{1/2%tsp} for the sauce and @chicken stock paste{10%g}
into the pan. Bring to the boil and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its packaging.

Lower the heat slightly and simmer until thickened, ~{8-10%minutes}.

Once thickened, add the @baby spinach{100%g} to the sauce a handful at a time
until wilted and piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Simmer until the sauce has reduced slightly and the chicken is cooked through,
~{3-4%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Stir through the @mango chutney{40%g} and @butter{20%g}.

Taste and season with salt and pepper if needed. Add a splash more water if
you feel it needs it.

Fluff up the rice with a #fork{}, then share between your #bowls{}.

Top with the chicken curry.

Enjoy!